Linux capabilities.

The default container already drops about half of linux's roughly forty capabilities, but the set that remains is still fairly large and includes some that have led to escapes in the past. The hardened baseline is to drop all capabilities and then add back exactly the ones the app actually needs. For most application code, that addition is nothing at all. For something that binds a low port, you add just the bind-low-ports capability. For something that needs to change file ownership, you add just the change-owner capability. In compose, you express this by setting cap-drop to all and cap-add to the short list you genuinely require.

It helps to know a handful of capabilities by what they do. There is one for binding ports below one thousand twenty-four, common for web servers running as non-root. There is one for changing file ownership outside your own user, used by init scripts that fix permissions. There are ones for changing user or group I-D after start, used by servers that drop privileges once they have bound their port. There is one for network administration, needed by v-p-n containers and network appliances. And there is the near-root sys-admin capability, which grants mounting and much more, which you should avoid because app workloads almost never need it.

Finally, the grand fail-safe to understand and avoid. The privileged flag grants every capability and drops the secure-computing and app-armor profiles entirely. Use it only when you can clearly articulate why no other combination works, in narrow cases like running docker inside docker or low-level hardware access. Reaching for privileged because something would not work otherwise is almost always a sign to find the specific capability you are missing instead.
